TextChange: Growing up, I always felt like the odd man out.  I had an older sister who was very close to my mother, and I also had a younger brother who was very close to my father.  My sister didn't like sharing my mother.  I think experiencing this at a young age may have helped me to tune into other's needs instinctually.  My earliest memories of helping others started before I even entered kindergarden.  I would bring homenstray dogs  in need.  I'd be so concerned for their well being such as no family to love them, no food, etc.  I never understood how my mother would make me return them to the streets without a care in the world.  Then in the second grade, I saw an elderly woman standing in front of her home as I walked home from school.  She waved at me and smiled.  I waved and smiled back.  Then a few days later, I noticed some strange noises coming from her home.  I knocked on her door to tell her about the noises, and the nice woman brought me outside to show me a raven she kept as a pet after it had broken its wing.  Our friendship started there.  I knew how happy this lonely woman was even at only age seven, and I tried to regularly visit her until I had to go to a different school.\n\n  I had wanted to go to nursing school when I graduated high school and started to apply to schools when my father told me about a job working in stocks in San Francisco.  I took that job with the idea of saving my money for college.  Unfortunately, letting go of the money I made was hard to do at a young age.  I worked at two brokerage firms before moving across the country.  I held some other office jobs in New England before becoming a stay at home mother.  No office work was rewarding.  The money never made me happy.  So after being a stay at home mom for 10 years, I decided it was time to do something for myself.  At that time, I started my own rescue of animals. In my early twenties, I decided to start nursing school.  I did not get far before I learned that my husband and I would be expecting our first child.  After about 10 years of being a stay at home mom, I got my children involved in helping families in need.  I also started my very own rescue farm and took in many abused and neglected animals.  Showing my children how to care for the needs of these animals, and watching them thrive, was more rewarding to me than any paying job could ever give me.  We had so many rich experiences to share with our family and friends and started to host gatherings at our home to share our experience.
